1. What @Component Does
When a class is annotated with @Component, Spring:

Scans the project and finds the class

Creates one object (a bean) of that class

Stores it inside the ApplicationContext

Registers it under its type (e.g., EmailService)

Example:

java
@Component
public class EmailService {
    public void sendEmail(String to) {
        System.out.println("Sending email to " + to);
    }
}
Spring creates one bean of type EmailService.

2. Declaring a Dependency in Another Class
Inside another class, we declare:

java
private final EmailService emailService;
Meaning:

EmailService → type

emailService → variable name

final → cannot be reassigned after constructor

private → only this class can use it

This is just an empty reference waiting for Spring to fill it.

3. Constructor Injection
Spring injects dependencies through the constructor:

java
@Component
public class UserService {

    private final EmailService emailService;

    @Autowired
    public UserService(EmailService emailService) {
        this.emailService = emailService;
    }

    public void registerUser(String email) {
        System.out.println("User registered");
        emailService.sendEmail(email);
    }
}
How it works:

Spring sees that UserService needs an EmailService

Spring already created an EmailService bean

Spring calls the constructor:

Code
new UserService(emailServiceBean)
Inside the constructor:

Code
this.emailService = emailService;
→ The dependency is stored permanently (because of final)

4. Why Constructor Injection Is Preferred
Guarantees the dependency is provided

Prevents null dependencies

Makes the class immutable

Works perfectly with final

Easier to test

Recommended by Spring

5. ApplicationContext and getBean()
The main() method is not managed by Spring, so we cannot use @Autowired there.

We must manually request beans from the container:

java
@SpringBootApplication
public class DemoApplication {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ApplicationContext context = SpringApplication.run(DemoApplication.class, args);

        UserService userService = context.getBean(UserService.class);
        userService.registerUser("shaktihazaru@gmail.com");
    }
}
Flow:

SpringApplication.run()
→ Starts Spring
→ Creates all beans
→ Performs dependency injection
→ Returns ApplicationContext

context.getBean(UserService.class)  
→ Fetches the same UserService bean Spring created

userService.registerUser(...)  
→ Uses the injected EmailService to send email

6. Full Flow Summary
@Component → Spring creates beans

Spring injects dependencies via constructor

Beans are stored in ApplicationContext

In main(), we manually fetch beans using getBean()

Methods like registerUser() use injected dependencies

7. Key Takeaways
Spring injects by type, not by variable name

EmailService = type

emailService = variable

final ensures immutability

Constructor injection is the cleanest and safest

ApplicationContext holds all beans, but you must ask for them in main()

